    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-10-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="34"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d34">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/595.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-10-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 15, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Chou Tzu Chi, of the Foreign Office, told me today that Japan has a squadron
                    under waiting orders ready to sail for China and join Admiral Kawashima at
                    Hankow. The despatch two days before the outbreak of Military Attaché Saito to
                    Hankow instead <pb facs="0166" n="50" xml:id="pg_50"/> of to the manoeuvers, and
                    the arrival of the Japanese admiral at Hankow the day after the outbreak, are
                    regarded as suspicious. The Chinese Government has been for months fearful of
                    Japanese designs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Williams.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
